events.description: Vitiges, king of the Ostrogoths ends his siege of Rome and retreats to Ravenna, leaving the city to the victorious Byzantine general, Belisarius.
events.html: • 538 – Vitiges, king of the Ostrogoths ends his siege of Rome and retreats to Ravenna, leaving the city to the victorious Byzantine general, Belisarius.[1]

events.description: Election of Urban II as the 159th Pope of the Catholic Church. He is best known for initiating the Crusades.
events.html: • 1088 – Election of Urban II as the 159th Pope of the Catholic Church. He is best known for initiating the Crusades.[2]

events.description: German city Munich (München) is first mentioned as forum apud Munichen in the Augsburg arbitration by Holy Roman Emperor Friedrich I.
events.html: • 1158 – German city Munich (München) is first mentioned as forum apud Munichen in the Augsburg arbitration by Holy Roman Emperor Friedrich I.[3]

events.description: Start of the Siege of Maastricht, part of the Eighty Years' War.
events.html: • 1579 – Start of the Siege of Maastricht, part of the Eighty Years' War.[4]

events.description: Ignatius of Loyola and Francis Xavier, founders of the Society of Jesus, are canonized by the Roman Catholic Church.
events.html: • 1622 – Ignatius of Loyola and Francis Xavier, founders of the Society of Jesus, are canonized by the Roman Catholic Church.[5]

events.description: James II of England landed at Kinsale, starting the Williamite War in Ireland.
events.html: • 1689 – James II of England landed at Kinsale, starting the Williamite War in Ireland.[6]

events.description: Peninsular War: A day after a successful rearguard action, French Marshal Michel Ney once again successfully delays the pursuing Anglo-Portuguese force at the Battle of Redinha.
events.html: • 1811 – Peninsular War: A day after a successful rearguard action, French Marshal Michel Ney once again successfully delays the pursuing Anglo-Portuguese force at the Battle of Redinha.[7]

events.description: The Girl Guides (later renamed the Girl Scouts of the USA) are founded in the United States.
events.html: • 1912 – The Girl Guides (later renamed the Girl Scouts of the USA) are founded in the United States.[8]

events.description: The future capital of Australia is officially named Canberra.
events.html: • 1913 – The future capital of Australia is officially named Canberra.[9]

events.description: Moscow becomes the capital of Russia again after Saint Petersburg held this status for most of the period since 1713.
events.html: • 1918 – Moscow becomes the capital of Russia again after Saint Petersburg held this status for most of the period since 1713.[10]

events.description: The Kapp Putsch begins when the Marinebrigade Ehrhardt is ordered to march on Berlin.
events.html: • 1920 – The Kapp Putsch begins when the Marinebrigade Ehrhardt is ordered to march on Berlin.[11]

events.description: In California, the St. Francis Dam fails; the resulting floods kill 431 people.
events.html: • 1928 – In California, the St. Francis Dam fails; the resulting floods kill 431 people.[12]

events.description: Mahatma Gandhi begins the Salt March, a 200-mile (320 km) march to the sea to protest the British monopoly on salt in India.
events.html: • 1930 – Mahatma Gandhi begins the Salt March, a 200-mile (320 km) march to the sea to protest the British monopoly on salt in India.[13]

events.description: Great Depression: Franklin D. Roosevelt addresses the nation for the first time as President of the United States. This is also the first of his "fireside chats".
events.html: • 1933 – Great Depression: Franklin D. Roosevelt addresses the nation for the first time as President of the United States. This is also the first of his "fireside chats".[8]

events.description: Anschluss: German troops occupy and annex Austria.
events.html: • 1938 – Anschluss: German troops occupy and annex Austria.[14]

events.description: Winter War: Finland signs the Moscow Peace Treaty with the Soviet Union, ceding almost all of Finnish Karelia.
events.html: • 1940 – Winter War: Finland signs the Moscow Peace Treaty with the Soviet Union, ceding almost all of Finnish Karelia.[15]

events.description: The most destructive train accident in Finnish history kills 39 and injures 69 people in Turenki, Janakkala.
events.html: • 1940 – The most destructive train accident in Finnish history kills 39 and injures 69 people in Turenki, Janakkala.[16]

events.description: The Battle of Java ends with the surrender of the American-British-Dutch-Australian Command to the Japanese Empire in Bandung, West Java, Dutch East Indies.
events.html: • 1942 – The Battle of Java ends with the surrender of the American-British-Dutch-Australian Command to the Japanese Empire in Bandung, West Java, Dutch East Indies.[17]

events.description: Cold War: The Truman Doctrine is proclaimed to help stem the spread of Communism.
events.html: • 1947 – Cold War: The Truman Doctrine is proclaimed to help stem the spread of Communism.[18]

events.description: The Llandow air disaster kills 80 people when the aircraft they are travelling in crashes near Sigingstone, Wales. At the time this was the world's deadliest air disaster.
events.html: • 1950 – The Llandow air disaster kills 80 people when the aircraft they are travelling in crashes near Sigingstone, Wales. At the time this was the world's deadliest air disaster.[19]

events.description: Suharto takes power from Sukarno when the People's Consultative Assembly inaugurate him as Acting President of Indonesia.
events.html: • 1967 – Suharto takes power from Sukarno when the People's Consultative Assembly inaugurate him as Acting President of Indonesia.[20]

events.description: Mauritius gains independence from the United Kingdom.
events.html: • 1968 – Mauritius gains independence from the United Kingdom.[21]

events.description: The 1971 Turkish military memorandum is sent to the Süleyman Demirel government of Turkey and the government resigns.
events.html: • 1971 – The 1971 Turkish military memorandum is sent to the Süleyman Demirel government of Turkey and the government resigns.[22]

events.description: Sir Tim Berners-Lee submits his proposal to CERN for an information management system, which subsequently develops into the World Wide Web.
events.html: • 1989 – Sir Tim Berners-Lee submits his proposal to CERN for an information management system, which subsequently develops into the World Wide Web.[23]

events.description: Mauritius becomes a republic while remaining a member of the Commonwealth of Nations.
events.html: • 1992 – Mauritius becomes a republic while remaining a member of the Commonwealth of Nations.[24]

events.description: Several bombs explode in Mumbai, India, killing about 300 people and injuring hundreds more.
events.html: • 1993 – Several bombs explode in Mumbai, India, killing about 300 people and injuring hundreds more.[25]

events.description: North Korea announces that it will withdraw from the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons and refuses to allow inspectors access to its nuclear sites.
events.html: • 1993 – North Korea announces that it will withdraw from the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons and refuses to allow inspectors access to its nuclear sites.[26]

entities.name: Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons

events.description: Former Warsaw Pact members the Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland join NATO.
events.html: • 1999 – Former Warsaw Pact members the Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland join NATO.[27]

events.description: Zoran Đinđić, Prime Minister of Serbia, is assassinated in Belgrade.
events.html: • 2003 – Zoran Đinđić, Prime Minister of Serbia, is assassinated in Belgrade.[28]

events.description: The World Health Organization officially release a global warning of outbreaks of Severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS).
events.html: • 2003 – The World Health Organization officially release a global warning of outbreaks of Severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS).[29]

events.description: The President of South Korea, Roh Moo-hyun, is impeached by its National Assembly: the first such impeachment in the nation's history.
events.html: • 2004 – The President of South Korea, Roh Moo-hyun, is impeached by its National Assembly: the first such impeachment in the nation's history.[30]

events.description: Financier Bernie Madoff pleads guilty to one of the largest frauds in Wall Street's history.
events.html: • 2009 – Financier Bernie Madoff pleads guilty to one of the largest frauds in Wall Street's history.[31]

events.description: A reactor at the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant explodes and releases radioactivity into the atmosphere a day after the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami.
events.html: • 2011 – A reactor at the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant explodes and releases radioactivity into the atmosphere a day after the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami.[32]

events.description: A gas explosion in the New York City neighborhood of East Harlem kills eight and injures 70 others.
events.html: • 2014 – A gas explosion in the New York City neighborhood of East Harlem kills eight and injures 70 others.[33]

events.description: US-Bangla Airlines Flight 211 crashes at Tribhuvan International Airport in Katmandu, killing 51 and injuring 20.
events.html: • 2018 – US-Bangla Airlines Flight 211 crashes at Tribhuvan International Airport in Katmandu, killing 51 and injuring 20.[34]

events.description: In the House of Commons, the revised EU Withdrawal Bill was rejected by a margin of 149 votes.
events.html: • 2019 – In the House of Commons, the revised EU Withdrawal Bill was rejected by a margin of 149 votes.[35]

events.description: The United States suspends travel from Europe due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
events.html: • 2020 – The United States suspends travel from Europe due to the COVID-19 pandemic.[36]
